canonical:
  title: 跋護法論
  author: 李穡
  language: lzh
  text: 宋丞相張天覺護法論一篇殆萬餘言釋僧俊以幻菴普濟大禪師之命重刊于忠之靑龍寺旣訖携墨本求予跋其尾予觀其辭率不可解然喜闢韓歐氏韓歐氏吾所師也吾實駭焉雖然五濁惡世爲善未必福爲惡未必禍非佛何所歸哉嗚呼護法論宜其盛行於世也
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 跋護法論
  author: 李穡
  language: lzh
  text: 宋丞相張天覺護法論一篇。殆萬餘言。釋僧俊以幻菴普濟大禪師之命。重刊于忠之靑龍寺。旣訖。携墨本。求予跋其尾。予觀其辭。率不可解。然喜闢韓，歐氏。韓，歐氏吾所師也。吾實駭焉。雖然。五濁惡世。爲善未必福。爲惡。未必禍。非佛何所歸哉。嗚呼。護法論。宜其盛行於世也。
korean:
  title: 발 호법론
  author: 이색
  language: kor
  text: 송(宋)나라 승상 장천각(張天覺)의 《호법론》 한 편이 거의 만여 자에 달한다. 석씨의 도제 승준(僧俊)이 환암 보제대선사(幻菴普濟大禪師)의 명으로 충주(忠州)  청룡사(靑龍寺)에서 이를 중간하였는데, 이미 공역을 마치고는 원본을 가지고 나에게 그 말미에 발하기를 요구해 왔다. 내가 그 말을 보니 거의 다 이해 할 수 없는 말들이다. 그러나 한(韓 한유)ㆍ구(歐 구양수)씨를 배척하기를 좋아하였으니, 한ㆍ구씨는 내가 본받는 바인지라, 내 실로 해괴하게 안다. 하지만 오탁악세(五濁惡世 불교에서는 인류가 생존하는 세계를 오탁악세라 부른다.)에서는 착한 일을 하여도 반드시 복되지 않으며, 악한 짓을 하여도 반드시 화 되지 않는다 하니, 불씨가 아니면 어디에 귀의하겠는가. 아, 《호법론》이 세상에 성행함은 의당한 일이로다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_1050_010_0310&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Colophon to the Defense of the Dharma
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Zhang Tiangjue, Chancellor of the Song Dynasty, composed a 'Defense of the Dharma'—a work stretching nearly ten thousand words. The monk Seungjun, disciple of the Buddhist order, undertook at the command of the Great Zen Master Hwanham Pojae to republish it at the Cheongnyong Temple in Chungju. Upon completion, he brought the original manuscript and asked me to write a colophon.

    I examined its words, and found most of them difficult to comprehend. Yet I admired how it refutes Han Yu and Ouyang Xiu—these very masters I myself have studied and revered. I confess this leaves me perplexed.

    But consider: in this world of five defilements, doing good does not necessarily bring blessing, nor does doing evil necessarily bring calamity. What refuge remains save in the Buddha? Alas! It is only fitting that the 'Defense of the Dharma' should flourish throughout the realm.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Han Yu (韓愈, 768–824) and Ouyang Xiu (歐陽修, 1007–1072) were Neo-Confucian thinkers whose rationalist critiques challenged Buddhist philosophy in China.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five defilements' (오탁, five corruptions) refers to the Buddhist cosmological concept that describes a corrupt age characterized by defilements of time, life, sentient beings, views, and afflictions.
  - key: ''
    value: This colophon reveals Lee Saek's intellectual struggle between his Confucian training and Buddhist thought—admiring the logical defense of Buddhism while maintaining philosophical loyalty to his Confucian masters.
